- ## GoalDriven

The approach of Oshiro, Watahiki and Saeki [12] is idea- driven and stakeholder centered. Based on goals each  stakeholder "thinks anything related to the selected goal and  makes it concrete as an idea". Afterwards these ideas get  grouped and attached to goals. Van Lamsweerde and Letier  [10] introduce a concept called obstacle for refining goals.

- ## GoalDriven
#GoalDriven #Eliciting #QRs #Challenges #NonFunctional #Requirements #Software #Engineering 
In some approaches, asking HOW and WHY questions  leads to new goals. Asking WHY questions facilitate the  elicitation of higher-ranking goals, while HOW questions lead  to new sub-goals (see [9], [16]).

- ## GoalDriven
#GoalDriven #Eliciting #QRs #Challenges #NonFunctional #Requirements #Software #Engineering 
One problem of most goal-oriented approaches is the lack  of a clear distinction between goals and requirements.  Questioning "when to stop refinement" highlights this issue.  Goal refinement in [10] proceeds until the goals are assignable  to so-called agents (i.e. humans, devices and software).  However, when is a goal assignable to an agent? According to  Robinson and Elofson [16], refining goals stops if the goal  descriptions do not refer to so-called domain properties, which  exist naturally in the environment.
